About
Picture it: 50,000 people on their feet, roaring with one voice, as gladiators below lock weapons and fight for fame, riches, and favor with the emperor. It’s easy to imagine this cinematic scene in the Colosseum. Although it’s been almost 2,000 years since ancient Romans used it for their mass entertainment, this stadium—now a UNESCO World Heritage site— still conveys epic grandeur, complete with those famous columned arcades. Inside, you’ll see a partially restored arena floor that acts as a platform above the “hypogeum”—the underground labyrinth of rooms and passageways that would have been the backstage area for the day’s entertainment. Look up, and you’ll spot tiered seating stretching up several levels. (V.I.P. seating is down low by the action; your average citizen was up high in the nosebleeds.) Certain tickets will let you access the underground up close and walk the arena floor in the footsteps of famed gladiators—no sword and shield required.
Duration: More than 3 hours

Must-see highlights

  • Arena
    The arena is where the action happened back in the day—book a tour for the full scoop.
  • Underground
    The underground area, or hypogeum, is the subterranean tunnel network that held gladiators, animals, and more.
  • Gladiator's Gate
    Here’s where gladiators made their big entrance—you’ll need to book a tour to see it.
  • Colosseum Museum
    Go deep on the Colosseum’s history through the artifacts and reconstructions in the second-floor museum.
Things to know
  • Avoid coming mid-day (about 11 a.m. to 3 p.m.), when the Colosseum is busiest.
  • Hours change seasonally, but in general, the Colosseum closes an hour before sunset.
  • Tours will take your experience to the next level. You’ll get through the entry line faster, for one, and you’ll be able to really dig into the Colosseum’s fascinating history.
  • If you prefer to go it solo, be sure to book your ticket in advance anyway. You’ll get in faster, and you’ll get access (on the same ticket) to the Forum and Palatine Hill across the way. (Just be sure to hit the Colosseum first—it’s the most crowded.)
  • A general-admission ticket gets you access to the first and second floors. To see restricted areas like the arena and the hypogeum, you’ll have to book a tour.
The ancient Flavian Amphitheater was built by the Flavian emperors in 70 C.E. as a gift to the Roman people. As the largest Roman theater ever built, it was designed to house over 50,000 people, and had played host to gladiator games, plays and even public executions. Purchase skip-the-line tickets online to avoid long lines at the door, or join guided tours which allow for special access to restricted areas. While here, you might want to visit the adjacent Palatine Hill and Roman Forum as well. – Tripadvisor

Conquering Rome in 48 hours—is it even possible? Sure, if what you have in mind is eating a slice of Roman-style pizza right out of a wood-fired oven, sampling a few flavors of gelato that you’ve never heard of, and joining locals as they stroll around the nearest piazza. This two-day itinerary lets you get a real feel for Rome while also savoring a handful of its showstoppers, including the Colosseum and the Sistine Chapel.
